# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: argocd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:argocd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:argocd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:argocd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:argocd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:argocd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:argocd/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:argocd/core-concepts] Let's assume you're familiar with core Git, Docker, Kubernetes, Continuous Delivery, and GitOps concepts.
[src:argocd/core-concepts] Below are some of the concepts that are specific to Argo CD.
[src:argocd/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:argocd/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:argocd/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:argocd/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:argocd/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:argocd/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:argocd/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:argocd/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:argocd/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:argocd/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:argocd/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:argocd/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:argocd/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:argocd/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:argocd/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:argocd/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:argocd/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:argocd/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:argocd/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:argocd/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:argocd/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:argocd/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:argocd/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:argocd/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:argocd/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:argocd/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:argocd/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:argocd/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:argocd/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:argocd/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:argocd/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:argocd/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:argocd/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:argocd/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:argocd/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:argocd/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:argocd/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:argocd/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:argocd/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:argocd/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:argocd/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:argocd/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:argocd/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:argocd/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:argocd/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:argocd/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:argocd/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:argocd/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:argocd/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:argocd/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:argocd/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:argocd/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:argocd/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:argocd/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:argocd/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:argocd/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:argocd/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:argocd/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:argocd/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:argocd/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:argocd/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:argocd/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:argocd/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:argocd/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:argocd/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:argocd/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:argocd/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:argocd/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:argocd/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:argocd/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:argocd/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:argocd/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:argocd/getting-started] This guide assumes you have a grounding in the tools that Argo CD is based on.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Please read understanding the basics to learn about these tools.
[src:argocd/getting-started] This will create a new `argocd` namespace where all Argo CD services and application resources will reside.
[src:argocd/getting-started] It will also install Argo CD by applying the official manifests from the stable branch.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Using a pinned version (like `v3.2.0`) is recommended for production.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The `--server-side` flag is required because some Argo CD CRDs (like ApplicationSet) exceed the 262KB annotation size limit imposed by client-side `kubectl apply`.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Server-side apply avoids this limitation by not storing the `last-applied-configuration` annotation.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The `--force-conflicts` flag allows the apply operation to take ownership of fields that may have been previously managed by other tools (such as Helm or a previous `kubectl apply`).
[src:argocd/getting-started] This is safe for fresh installs and necessary for upgrades.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Note that any custom modifications you've made to fields that are defined in the Argo CD manifests (like `affinity`, `env`, or `probes`) will be overwritten.
[src:argocd/getting-started] However, fields not specified in the manifests (like `resources` limits/requests or `tolerations`) will be preserved.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The installation manifests include `ClusterRoleBinding` resources that reference `argocd` namespace.
[src:argocd/getting-started] If you are installing Argo CD into a different namespace then make sure to update the namespace reference.
[src:argocd/getting-started] If you are not interested in UI, SSO, and multi-cluster features, then you can install only the core Argo CD components.
[src:argocd/getting-started] This default installation will have a self-signed certificate and cannot be accessed without a bit of extra work.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Default namespace for `kubectl` config must be set to `argocd`.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Use `argocd login --core` to configure CLI access and skip steps 3-5.
[src:argocd/getting-started] This default installation for Redis is using password authentication.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The Redis password is stored in Kubernetes secret `argocd-redis` with key `auth` in the namespace where Argo CD is installed.
[src:argocd/getting-started] If you are running Argo CD on Docker Desktop or another local Kubernetes environment, refer to the Running Argo CD Locally guide for the full setup instructions and configuration steps tailored for local clusters.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Download the latest Argo CD version from https://github.com/argoproj/argo-cd/releases/latest.
[src:argocd/getting-started] More detailed installation instructions can be found via the CLI installation documentation.
[src:argocd/getting-started] By default, Argo CD isn’t exposed outside the cluster.
[src:argocd/getting-started] `kubectl patch svc argocd-server -n argocd -p '{"spec": {"type": "LoadBalancer"}}'` After a short wait, your cloud provider will assign an external IP address to the service.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Follow the ingress documentation on how to configure Argo CD with ingress.
[src:argocd/getting-started] `kubectl port-forward` can also be used to connect to the API server without exposing the service.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The initial password for the `admin` account is auto-generated and stored as clear text in the field `password` in a secret named `argocd-initial-admin-secret` in your Argo CD installation namespace.
[src:argocd/getting-started] You should delete the `argocd-initial-admin-secret` from the Argo CD namespace once you changed the password.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The secret serves no other purpose than to store the initially generated password in clear and can safely be deleted at any time.
[src:argocd/getting-started] It will be re-created on demand by Argo CD if a new admin password must be re-generated.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The CLI environment must be able to communicate with the Argo CD API server.
[src:argocd/getting-started] This step registers a cluster's credentials to Argo CD, and is only necessary when deploying to an external cluster.
[src:argocd/getting-started] When deploying internally (to the same cluster that Argo CD is running in), https://kubernetes.default.svc should be used as the application's K8s API server address.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Choose a context name from the list and supply it to `argocd cluster add CONTEXTNAME`.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The above command installs a ServiceAccount (`argocd-manager`), into the kube-system namespace of that kubectl context, and binds the service account to an admin-level ClusterRole.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Argo CD uses this service account token to perform its management tasks (i.e. deploy/monitoring).
[src:argocd/getting-started] The rules of the `argocd-manager-role` role can be modified such that it only has `create`, `update`, `patch`, `delete` privileges to a limited set of namespaces, groups, kinds.
[src:argocd/getting-started] However `get`, `list`, `watch` privileges are required at the cluster-scope for Argo CD to function.
[src:argocd/getting-started] An example repository containing a guestbook application is available at https://github.com/argoproj/argocd-example-apps.git to demonstrate how Argo CD works.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The following example application may only be compatible with AMD64 architecture.
[src:argocd/getting-started] If you are running on a different architecture (such as ARM64 or ARMv7), you may encounter issues with dependencies or container images that are not built for your platform.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Consider verifying the compatibility of the application or building architecture-specific images if necessary.
[src:argocd/getting-started] Open a browser to the Argo CD external UI, and login by visiting the IP/hostname in a browser and use the credentials set in step 4 or locally as explained in Try Argo CD Locally.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The application status is initially in `OutOfSync` state since the application has yet to be deployed, and no Kubernetes resources have been created.
[src:argocd/getting-started] This command retrieves the manifests from the repository and performs a `kubectl apply` of the manifests.
[src:argocd/getting-started] The guestbook app is now running and you can now view its resource components, logs, events, and assessed health status.
[src:argocd/getting-started] A panel will be opened and then, click on *Synchronize* button.
[src:argocd/page] Argo CD is a declarative, GitOps continuous delivery tool for Kubernetes.
[src:argocd/page] Application definitions, configurations, and environments should be declarative and version controlled.
[src:argocd/page] Application deployment and lifecycle management should be automated, auditable, and easy to understand.
[src:argocd/page] The `--server-side --force-conflicts` flags are required due to CRD size limitations.
[src:argocd/page] See the getting started guide for details.
[src:argocd/page] Further user oriented documentation is provided for additional features.
[src:argocd/page] If you are looking to upgrade Argo CD, see the upgrade guide.
[src:argocd/page] Developer oriented documentation is available for people interested in building third-party integrations.
[src:argocd/page] Argo CD follows the **GitOps** pattern of using Git repositories as the source of truth for defining the desired application state.
[src:argocd/page] Argo CD automates the deployment of the desired application states in the specified target environments.
[src:argocd/page] Application deployments can track updates to branches, tags, or be pinned to a specific version of manifests at a Git commit.
[src:argocd/page] See tracking strategies for additional details about the different tracking strategies available.
[src:argocd/page] Argo CD is implemented as a Kubernetes controller which continuously monitors running applications and compares the current, live state against the desired target state (as specified in the Git repo).
[src:argocd/page] A deployed application whose live state deviates from the target state is considered `OutOfSync`.
[src:argocd/page] Argo CD reports & visualizes the differences, while providing facilities to automatically or manually sync the live state back to the desired target state.
[src:argocd/page] Any modifications made to the desired target state in the Git repo can be automatically applied and reflected in the specified target environments.
[src:argocd/page] For additional details, see architecture overview.
[src:argocd/page] Argo CD is being actively developed by the community.
[src:argocd/page] A growing list of organizations(https://github.com/argoproj/argo-cd/blob/master/USERS.md) have officially adopted Argo CD.
